ontemporary world. Locating profound ambivalence in people's ethical evaluations of gender and fertility control, Paxson offers a far-reaching analysis of conflicting assumptions about what it takes to be a good mother and a good woman in modern Greece, where assertions of cultural tradition unfold against a backdrop of European Union integration, economic struggle, and national demographic anxiety over a falling birth rate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBirth controlxPublic opinionxGreecexAthens. 0aBirth controlzGreecezAthensxPublic opinion. 0aFeminist anthropologyxGreecexAthens. 0aFeminist anthropologyzGreecezAthens. 0aMotherhoodxGreecexAthens. 0aMotherhoodzGreecezAthens. 0aPublic opinionxGreecexAthens. 0aPublic opinionzGreecezAthens. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxGreecexAthens. 0aWomenzGreecezAthensxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937130423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520937130.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles